adtostudy.com/#logo"}},{"@type":"WebSite","@id":"https://roadtostudy.com/#website","url":"https://roadtostudy.com","name":"Road to Study - Turkey University Guide for Students","alternateName":"Road to Study in Turkey","publisher":{"@id":"https://roadtostudy.com/#person"},"inLanguage":"en-US"},{"@type":"WebPage","@id":"https://roadtostudy.com/en/from-ottoman-to-modern-turkish-the-effects-of-the-language-reform/#webpage","url":"https://roadtostudy.com/en/from-ottoman-to-modern-turkish-the-effects-of-the-language-reform/","name":"From Ottoman to Modern Turkish: The Effects of the Language Reform - RoadtoStudy","datePublished":"2026-06-20T10:00:00+03:00","dateModified":"2026-06-20T10:00:00+03:00","isPartOf":{"@id":"https://roadtostudy.com/#website"},"inLanguage":"en-US"},{"@type":"Person","@id":"https://roadtostudy.com/en/author/murat/","name":"Murat","url":"https://roadtostudy.com/en/author/murat/","image":{"@type":"ImageObject","@id":"https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/9f5b866231ae7aed7a61015846c1f0ab6c5797b065ec200b93c5e9daa87897af?s=96&amp;d=mm&amp;r=g","url":"https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/9f5b866231ae7aed7a61015846c1f0ab6c5797b065ec200b93c5e9daa87897af?s=96&amp;d=mm&amp;r=g","caption":"Murat","inLanguage":"en-US"}},{"@type":"BlogPosting","headline":"From Ottoman to Modern Turkish: The Effects of the Language Reform - RoadtoStudy","datePublished":"2026-06-20T10:00:00+03:00","dateModified":"2026-06-20T10:00:00+03:00","articleSection":"Health and Safety","author":{"@id":"https://roadtostudy.com/en/author/murat/","name":"Murat"},"publisher":{"@id":"https://roadtostudy.com/#person"},"description":"Explore the transition from Ottoman to modern Turkish. Read our article now to learn about the societal impacts of the language reform!","name":"From Ottoman to Modern Turkish: The Effects of the Language Reform - RoadtoStudy","@id":"https://roadtostudy.com/en/from-ottoman-to-modern-turkish-the-effects-of-the-language-reform/#richSnippet","isPartOf":{"@id":"https://roadtostudy.com/en/from-ottoman-to-modern-turkish-the-effects-of-the-language-reform/#webpage"},"inLanguage":"en-US","mainEntityOfPage":{"@id":"https://roadtostudy.com/en/from-ottoman-to-modern-turkish-the-effects-of-the-language-reform/#webpage"}}]}]}', "content_html" = '<p class="wp-block-paragraph">Turkey&#8217;s linguistic history has been shaped by the transition process from Ottoman to modern Turkish. This article will cover the fundamental characteristics of Ottoman Turkish, the reasons for the transition to modern Turkish, the languages that influenced Ottoman Turkish, when Turkish became the official language in the Ottoman era, the differences between Ottoman and modern Turkish, and the place of Ottoman Turkish in the education system.</p>
<h2 id="osmanlica-nedir-temel-ozellikleri-ve-tarihcesi" class="wp-block-heading">What is Ottoman Turkish? Its Basic Features and History</h2>
<p class="wp-block-paragraph">Ottoman Turkish is a language used during the Ottoman Empire period and was written in the Arabic script. This language has a complex structure, formed from a combination of Turkish, Arabic, and Persian. Ottoman Turkish was widely used, especially in literary works and official documents. Historically, the origins of Ottoman Turkish date back to the 13th century, and the language&#8217;s richness grew with the expansion of the empire.</p>
<h3 class="wp-block-heading">Basic Features</h3>
<ul class="wp-block-list">
<li><strong>Alphabet:</strong> Ottoman Turkish is written in the Arabic script and read from right to left.</li>
<li><strong>Complex Structure:</strong> The language was enriched by the extensive use of Arabic and Persian words built upon Turkish roots.</li>
<li><strong>Literature:</strong> Ottoman Turkish holds a significant place, especially in Divan literature. Poets and writers skillfully used the subtleties of the Ottoman language.</li>
</ul>
<h2 id="modern-turkceye-gecis-neden-ve-nasil" class="wp-block-heading">The Transition to Modern Turkish: Why and How?</h2>
<div id="chat-history" class="chat-history-scroll-container">
<div id="8f4a3a0efde19376" class="conversation-container message-actions-hover-boundary ng-star-inserted">
<div class="response-container ng-tns-c4239732258-22 response-container-with-gpi ng-star-inserted response-container-has-multiple-responses">
<div class="presented-response-container ng-tns-c4239732258-22">
<div class="response-container-content ng-tns-c4239732258-22">
<div class="response-content ng-tns-c4239732258-22">
<div id="model-response-message-contentr_8f4a3a0efde19376" class="markdown markdown-main-panel stronger enable-updated-hr-color" dir="ltr">
<p>The transition to modern Turkish was a comprehensive and multi-layered process that extended from the final period of the Ottoman Empire to the early years of the Republic. Behind this transformation lay both political and social reasons, as well as issues stemming from the language&#8217;s own internal structure.</p>
<h4>Reasons</h4>
<ol start="1">
<li><b>The Problem of Incomprehensibility:</b> Ottoman Turkish had a complex structure composed heavily of Arabic and Persian words, making it unintelligible to the vast majority of the population. While intellectuals and the palace circle used this language, known as &#8220;High Ottoman,&#8221; the public spoke &#8220;crude Turkish,&#8221; which consisted of simpler, local words. This situation caused a significant communication gap between different segments of society.</li>
<li><b>Building a National Identity:</b> As the multinational structure of the Ottoman Empire gave way to a new nation-state, the Republic of Turkey, the need to create a common national identity arose. One of the cornerstones of this identity was a common and simple language. A version of Turkish that everyone could understand, purified of foreign influences, was seen as a tool to strengthen national unity.</li>
<li><b>The Goal of Increasing Literacy:</b> The Arabic script did not fully suit the sound structure of Turkish. The lack of sufficient vowels, in particular, made reading and writing difficult. The Republic&#8217;s goal of rapidly increasing the literacy rate with its new education system necessitated the replacement of this alphabet with one that was easier to learn and better suited to Turkish phonetics.</li>
</ol>
<h4>How Did It Happen?</h4>
<p>The transition process to modern Turkish consisted of various stages and significant steps:</p>
<ol start="1">
<li><b>Voluntary Efforts of Intellectuals (Tanzimat Period and After):</b> With the Westernization movements that began in the 19th century, literary movements like <b>Tanzimat, Servet-i Fünun, and Genç Kalemler</b> (Young Pens) made efforts to simplify the language and bring it closer to the people. In particular, the <b>Genç Kalemler</b> movement, led by <b>Ömer Seyfettin</b>, advocated for a national and simple Turkish under the name &#8220;Yeni Lisan&#8221; (New Language), preparing the intellectual groundwork for this transformation.</li>
<li><b>The Alphabet Revolution (1928):</b> The most radical and significant step in this process was the <b>Alphabet Revolution</b>, adopted on November 1, 1928. The use of the Arabic script was abolished and replaced with the <b>Latin alphabet</b>, which was better suited to Turkish phonetics. This revolution made it easier to learn to read and write, and the literacy rate rose rapidly in a short time.</li>
<li><b>Establishment of the Turkish Language Association (1932):</b> To carry out the work of simplifying and enriching the language on a scientific basis, <b>Mustafa Kemal Atatürk</b> founded the <b>Türk Dili Tetkik Cemiyeti</b> (Society for the Study of the Turkish Language), known today as the <b>Türk Dil Kurumu (TDK)</b>. The TDK undertook tasks such as finding Turkish equivalents for old Ottoman words, determining the rules of the language, and creating new terms, making a significant contribution to the modernization process of the language.</li>
<li><b>The Turkification of Words:</b> With the work of the TDK, thousands of words of Arabic and Persian origin began to be replaced by <b>&#8216;öz Türkçe&#8217;</b> (pure Turkish) words compiled from folk dialects or newly coined. For example, words like &#8216;öğretmen&#8217; (teacher) replaced &#8216;muallim,&#8217; &#8216;tarih&#8217; replaced &#8216;târih,&#8217; and &#8216;mahiyet&#8217; replaced &#8216;mâhiyet,&#8217; establishing their place in the language.</li>
</ol>
<p>This transformation was not just a change of alphabet, but also the result of an effort to create a national language and identity. The <b>Modern Turkish</b> we speak today is the product of these radical reforms.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<h2 id="osmanli-turkcesi-hangi-dillerden-etkilenmistir" class="wp-block-heading">What Languages Influenced Ottoman Turkish?</h2>
<p class="wp-block-paragraph">Ottoman Turkish was influenced by many languages throughout its <a href="https://roadtostudy.com/turkcenin-tarihi-gelisimi/">historical process</a>. The most prominent among these languages are:</p>
<ul class="wp-block-list">
<li><strong>Arabic:</strong> This was the most commonly used foreign language in Ottoman Turkish. Words of Arabic origin are frequently found, especially in religious and literary texts.</li>
<li><strong>Persian:</strong> Persian, which held an important place in Ottoman literature, contributed to the enrichment of the language.</li>
<li><strong>French:</strong> With increased relations with the West in the 19th century, French words entered Ottoman Turkish.</li>
</ul>
<h2 id="osmanlida-turkce-ne-zaman-resm-dil-olmustur" class="wp-block-heading">When Did Turkish Become the Official Language in the Ottoman Empire?</h2>
<p class="wp-block-paragraph">In the Ottoman Empire, Turkish was adopted as the official language towards the end of the 19th century. However, Ottoman Turkish was still widely used during this period. With the proclamation of the Republic, Turkish was adopted as the official language, and Turkish language education was prioritized in the education system.</p>
<h2 id="osmanlica-ve-modern-turkce-arasindaki-farklar" class="wp-block-heading">Differences Between Ottoman and Modern Turkish</h2>
<p class="wp-block-paragraph">There are distinct differences between Ottoman and modern Turkish:</p>
<ul class="wp-block-list">
<li><strong>Alphabet:</strong> While Ottoman Turkish is written in the Arabic script, modern Turkish uses the Latin alphabet.</li>
<li><strong>Complexity:</strong> Ottoman Turkish has a more complex grammatical structure. Modern Turkish, on the other hand, has a simpler and more understandable structure.</li>
<li><strong>Vocabulary:</strong> Ottoman Turkish contains many words of Arabic and Persian origin, whereas modern Turkish includes more words with Turkish roots.</li>
</ul>
<h2 id="egitim-sisteminde-osmanlicanin-yeri-ve-onemi" class="wp-block-heading">The Place and Importance of Ottoman Turkish in the Education System</h2>
<p class="wp-block-paragraph">Ottoman Turkish held a significant place in the education system until the Republican era. However, with the establishment of the Republic, Ottoman language classes were removed from the curriculum, and Turkish language education was prioritized.</p>
<h3 class="wp-block-heading">The Importance of Ottoman Turkish in Education</h3>
<ul class="wp-block-list">
<li><strong>Cultural Heritage:</strong> Ottoman Turkish is an important part of Turkish culture and literature. Ottoman texts play a major role in helping us understand our historical and cultural heritage.</li>
<li><strong>Linguistics:</strong> Studying Ottoman Turkish provides students with a different perspective on grammar and vocabulary.</li>
</ul>
<h2 id="sonuc" class="wp-block-heading">The Transition from Ottoman to Modern Turkish</h2>
<p class="wp-block-paragraph">The transition process from Ottoman to modern Turkish is a significant turning point in Turkey&#8217;s linguistic history. This process was realized through the simplification of the language and its transformation into a form that the public could understand. The place and importance of Ottoman Turkish in education play a critical role in understanding our cultural heritage. Modern Turkish, while preserving the richness inherited from the past, is also advancing on the path to becoming a contemporary language. For those wishing to study in Turkey, the history and development of this language is an important source of information.</p>
<h2 id="sik-sorulan-sorular-faq" class="wp-block-heading">Frequently Asked Questions (FAQ)</h2>
<h3 class="wp-block-heading">Is Ottoman Turkish difficult to learn?</h3>
<p class="wp-block-paragraph">Due to its complex structure, learning Ottoman Turkish can be challenging at first. However, it is possible to learn with regular study and practice.</p>
<h3 class="wp-block-heading">What is the biggest difference between Modern Turkish and Ottoman Turkish?</h3>
<p class="wp-block-paragraph">The biggest difference is the alphabet used and the complexity of the language. Ottoman Turkish is written in the Arabic script, while modern Turkish uses the Latin alphabet.</p>
<h3 class="wp-block-heading">What resources are recommended for learning Ottoman Turkish?</h3>
<p class="wp-block-paragraph">Language courses, books, and online resources can be used. Additionally, university Turkish Language and Literature departments also offer courses in Ottoman Turkish.</p>
<h3 class="wp-block-heading">What is the place of Ottoman Turkish today?</h3>
<p class="wp-block-paragraph">Today, Ottoman Turkish holds a significant place, especially in the fields of literature, history, and cultural studies. Furthermore, some universities offer courses in Ottoman Turkish.</p>
<h3 class="wp-block-heading">What languages influenced Ottoman Turkish?</h3>
<p class="wp-block-paragraph">Ottoman Turkish was influenced by languages such as Arabic, Persian, and French. These languages contributed to enriching the vocabulary of Ottoman Turkish.</p>', "wp_published_at" = '2026-06-20T07:00:00Z', "wp_modified_at" = '2026-03-16T19:53:27Z' WHERE "deleted_at" IS NULL AND "status" = 'published' AND "locale" = 'en' AND "slug" = 'from-ottoman-to-modern-turkish-the-effects-of-the-language-reform';
